			<h3 id="comments-title">23 Responses to <em>The Reactionary Consensus?</em></h3>


			<ol class="commentlist">
					<li class="comment byuser comment-author-alvarez80 even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-3">
		<div id="comment-3">
			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/784b522a01abab789b87ba2f835bb45b?s=40&#038;d=monsterid&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn"><a href='http://habitableworlds.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Scharlach</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
			
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://nickbsteves.wordpress.com/2013/05/07/the-reactionary-consensus/#comment-3">
				2013/05/07 at 21:21</a>			</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

			<div class="comment-body"><p><i> Traditional folkways tend to be real, i.e., non-ideological, and naturally arising adaptations to social realities, </i></p>
<p>I can&#8217;t remember if I pointed you in the direction of Razib Khan&#8217;s essay on empirical conservatism, but he makes the same point about trusting general folk wisdom until proven otherwise.</p>
<p>Anyway, glad to have you blogging! </p>
<p> but this is
