			<div class="comment-body"><p>Regarding hierarchy, one of the potential points of contention between the neo-reactionary factions you&#8217;ve defined is the list of factors that determine an individual&#8217;s place in a hierarchy. For example, if we all agree that I.Q. is a real phenomenon, which I suspect we do, is it necessary and sufficient, necessary but insufficient, or unnecessary and insufficient to determine am individual&#8217;s place. This issue is interesting to me because it concerns power, and the allocation of power is always where things get messy. IMO, the lack of an agreed way to allocate power is the most telling sign that few in the Reactionary movement believe that we are actually in any position to succeed <span class='wp-smiley emoji emoji-smile' title=':)'>:)</span>. If we thought we were going to win, we would have very clear and well documented ideas about how we are going to distribute power.</p>
<p> Very much like your post, though.
<p id="comment-like-13" data-liked=comment-not-liked class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://nickbsteves.wordpress.com/2013/05/07/the-reactionary-consensus/?like_comment=13&#038;_wpnonce=467ff97d38" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="51726726"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-13" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p>
